{"title_page": "1973\u201374 Yugoslav First League", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[Yugoslav First League|Prva savezna liga]]\n| season                     = 1973\u201374\n| winners                    = [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]<br />(5th Federal League title)<br />(7th Yugoslav title overall)\n| promoted                   =\n| relegated                  = [[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]<br>[[NK Zagreb]]\n| continentalcup1            = [[1974\u201375 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n| continentalcup2            = [[1974\u201375 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n| continentalcup3            = [[1974\u201375 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]<br />[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n| league topscorer           = [[Danilo Popivoda]] (17)\n| dates                      = {{nowrap|19 August 1973 \u2013 14 May 1974}}\n| biggest home win           =\n| biggest away win           =\n| highest scoring            =\n| total goals                =\n| average goals              =\n| longest wins               =\n| longest unbeaten           =\n| longest losses             =\n| highest attendance         =\n| lowest attendance          =\n| average attendance         =\n| prevseason                 = [[1972\u201373 Yugoslav First League|1972\u201373]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1974\u201375 Yugoslav First League|1974\u201375]]\n}}\n'''1973\u201374 Yugoslav First League''' (Prva savezna liga Jugoslavije, Prvenstvo 1973/74) competition was the 46th top league season since 1923 in various incarnations of Yugoslavia. It was won by [[NK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]] by the tightest of margins over second placed [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]. The two teams were tied on points at the end of the season, so the goal difference decided the title.\n\nHad the current three-points-for-a-win system been in use instead of the standard two-points-for-a-win that was used at the time, Vele\u017e Mostar would have been champions with 64 points, while Hajduk would have been be second with 63.\n\nThis was Hajduk's 7th league title overall (their 5th after the [[World War II]]).\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eighteen teams contested the league, including sixteen sides from the [[1972\u201373 Yugoslav First League|1972\u201373 season]] and two sides promoted from the 1972\u201373 [[Yugoslav Second League]] (YSL) as winners of the two second level divisions East and West. The league was contested in a [[double round robin]] format, with each club playing every other club twice, for a total of 34 rounds. Two points were awarded for wins and one point for draws.\n\n[[FK Spartak Zlatibor Voda|Spartak Subotica]] and [[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107]] were relegated from the [[1972\u201373 Yugoslav First League]] after finishing the season in bottom two places of the league table.  The two clubs promoted to top level were [[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]] and [[NK Zagreb]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n!width=\"130\"| Team\n!width=\"100\"| Location\n!width=\"200\"| [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia#Federal subjects|Federal Republic]]\n!width=\"90\"| Position<br />in [[1972\u201373 Yugoslav First League|1972\u201373]]\n|-\n|[[FK Bor|Bor]]\n|[[Bor, Serbia|Bor]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">015</span>15th\n|-\n|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|[[Banja Luka]]\n|{{flag|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">012</span>12th\n|-\n|[[NK \u010celik Zenica|\u010celik]]\n|[[Zenica]]\n|{{flag|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">014</span>14th\n|-\n|[[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|[[Zagreb]